      <hr noshade color="#0099cc" />
      <h2><a name="introduction" id="introduction">Overview</a></h2>
      <table border="0" align="right">
        <tr> 
          <td><img src="images/blueface.jpg" width="260" height="326" vspace="5" /></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td align="center"><a href="http://www.paulkasmingallery.com/"> <font size="-1">Claude 
            Heath, <em>Blue Face</em>, 1999</font></a></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <p>The new M.Phil. in Criticism and Culture, launched in October 2004, is 
        an innovative nine-month course of literary study with an interdisciplinary 
        and comparative focus, running from October until the end of June. It 
        aims to provide an introduction to and training in different aspects of 
        contemporary literary criticism and literary and cultural theory. You 
        will be encouraged to develop a critical and methodological framework, 
        and to pursue questions relating to literary and cultural production alongside 
        your individual research project. Within a flexible framework, you will 
        be able to study particular areas in depth or explore topics broadly relevant 
        to your intended research. Each student works closely with a member of 
        the Faculty on his or her chosen dissertation topic while participating 
        in collaborative seminars and classes. </p>
      <p></p>
      <p>The three-term course will consist of a changing program of seminars, 
        combined with a reading group and a dissertation group bringing students 
        together for collaborative exchange. You will write papers in the first 
        two terms, followed by a final dissertation on the research topic of your 
        choice. You will be able to construct an individual program tailored to 
        your research interests, in close consultation with an advisor who will 
        usually also serve as your dissertation supervisor for the third and final 
        term. All M.Phil. students are strongly encouraged to attend the English 
        Faculty's graduate research seminars, which consist of presentations by 
        outside speakers, faculty, and graduate students. You will also have the 
        chance to attend lectures in other fields in the Humanities and to explore 
        the interdisciplinary possibilities of graduate study at Cambridge. In 
        addition, you will be able to draw on the University's language-learning 
        facilities and exceptional library resources and special collections.</p>
      <p>The M.Phil. in Criticism and Culture is designed to provide a gateway 
        to a wide range of different research areas, including areas that are 
        historically based. You will be able to take courses and subjects from 
        other M.Phils. in English, as well as from M.Phils in certain other faculties 
        (see below). Registration for the Ph.D. on topics that fall within the 
        purview of the Criticism and Culture Graduate Subject Committee will normally 
        require students to have completed either the M.Phil. in Criticism and 
        Culture or one of the English Faculty's other M.Phils at an appropriate 
        level, or the equivalent at another university.<br />
      </p>
      <h2><img src="images/capital.jpg" width="192" height="271" align="left" vspace="5" style="padding-right:8px;" /><a name="course" id="course">The Course</a></h2>
      <p>Seminars run throughout the first two terms, Michaelmas and Lent. You 
        will be able to choose two courses per term from a changing selection 
        (usually three or four courses) on offer each term, depending on the research 
        interests and availability of academic staff. At least one course would 
        normally be drawn from the list of courses specific to the Criticism and 
        Culture M.Phil. (Option 
        A courses). In either term (timetable and availability permitting) qualified 
        students may opt to take one of their courses from another M.Phil. in 
        English or from an M.Phil. in certain other faculties (Option B courses). 
        M.Phils currently offered in English are <a href="MedRen_MPhil_Info.htm">Medieval 
        and Renaissance Literature</a>, <a href="1700_MPhil_Info.htm">18th Century 
        and Romantic Studies </a>, and <a href="AmLit_MPhil_Info.htm">American 
        Literature</a>. M.Phils. with which English has exchange arrangements 
        at present include European Literature (<a href="http://www.mml.cam.ac.uk/">Faculty 
        of Medieval and Modern Languages [MML]</a>), <a href="http://www.hoart.cam.ac.uk/"> 
        History of Art and Architecture</a>, and the History and Philosophy of 
        Science and Medicine (<a href="http://www.hps.cam.ac.uk/">Faculty of History 
        and Philosophy of Science [HPS]</a>).</p>
      <p>All courses meet weekly from weeks 2 to 7 for 1.5 hours (or longer by discretion of 
        the seminar-convenor). The Criticism &amp; Culture Reading Group meets 
        each week; the dissertation writing groups meet in 
      small student facilitated groups during Easter Term. </p>
      <p><br />
        <strong>Michaelmas Term 2006</strong></p>
      <p>Criticism &amp; Culture Reading Seminar (Professor M. Jacobus and Dr. 
        C. Cannon)</p>
      <p>Seminars</p>
    <p>      
    <li><a href="#Fleming"> Dr J. Fleming, Reading Grammatology</a></li>
      <li><a href="#Hillman"> Dr D. Hillman, The Body in Culture</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Milne">Dr A. Milne, Marxism and Critical Theory</a></li>
    <li>Dr C. Cannon, Hegelianism and Form: Commodities, Persons and Gender (not offered in 2006-2007) </li>
    </p>
    <p>Wed. 5 pm (weeks 1,3,5,7) Criticism &amp; Culture Graduate Research Seminar: 
      speaker series.<br />
      (Convenors, Professor M. Jacobus, Dr. D. Hillman)</p>
    <p><strong><br />
      Lent Term 2007</strong></p>
    <p>Criticism &amp; Culture Dissertation Proposal Workshop (Professor M. Jacobus 
      and Dr. D. Hillman)</p>
    <p>Seminars</p>
    
    <li><a href="#Trotter">Professor D. Trotter, 'Naturalism' in Literature and 
      Cinema</a></li>
    <li><a href="#Jacobus">Professor M. Jacobus, Psychoanalysis and Vision</a></li>
        <li></li>
        <a href="#Gopal">Dr P. Gopal, The Postcolonial Intellectual </a><br/>
    <p> Wed. 5 pm (weeks 1,3,5,7) Criticism &amp; Culture Graduate Research Seminar: 
      speaker series.<br />
      (Convenors, Professor M. Jacobus, Dr. D. Hillman)</p>
    <p><strong>Easter Term 2007</strong></p>
    <p>Criticism &amp; Culture dissertation writing groups (student facilitated)<br />
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Option A courses may be either conceptually or historically oriented, 
        or both, but in any year will include a selection of topics such as: philosophy 
        and poetry, Marxist literary criticism, theories of writing, performance 
        culture, post-colonial writing, visual culture, psychoanalytic literary 
        criticism, post-modern theory, literature and politics. Available options 
        will include a minimum of three courses in each of the first two terms 
        drawn from the following selection: <br />
        <br />
        <ul>
          <p><strong>Michaelmas Term</strong></p>
          <p><a name="Fleming" id="Fleming"><strong>DR J. FLEMING, Reading Grammatology</strong></a> </p>
          <p>Derrida claimed that the seeds of his subsequent writing were all
            contained in his earliest work; and, together with 'Writing and Difference'
            (1967), 'Of Grammatology' (1967) may be considered the seminal text
            of his oeuvre. This seminar will devote itself, not to learning about
            Derrida, but to reading what he wrote. to do this we will read the
            texts that Derrida attends to in 'Of Grammatology' (including writings
            by Levi-Strauss, Rousseau, Heidegger, Freud, and Andre Leroi Gourhan),
            while also reading his own text. By the end of the seminar members
            will have felt for themselves the movement, and experienced the influence
            , of Derrida's thought.</p>
          <p><a href= "Gramm.htm">(Reading)</a>          </p>
          <p><a name="Hillman" id="Hillman"><strong>DR. D. HILLMAN, The Body
                in Culture</strong></a>          
          <p>This course combines historical and theoretical perspectives on
            the  place of the body in culture, from early modernity through to
            modernist 
            conceptions of embodiment. The classes will examine specific literary
             texts, including Montaigne, Shakespeare, Mary Shelley, and Joyce,
            
            alongside theorists of the body, including Bakhtin, Nietzsche, Freud
             and Lacan. Some questions we will explore include: What part does
            
            the body play in the construction of self and other? What makes bodies
             such compelling objects of desire or repulsion? How is the immediate
            
            materiality of the body represented in literary texts? How, conversely,
             can the body itself be 'written' - marked and changed by ideological
            
            and historical forces? What, ultimately, can we say about the enigmatic
             relation between the body and language? </p>
			 <p><a href= "Body.htm">(Reading)</a>
          </p>
          <a name="Milne" id="Milne"><strong>DR D. MILNE, Marx and Marxist Literary
          Theory</strong></a>
          <p>Using the anthology MARXIST LITERARY THEORY: A READER, eds. Terry
            Eagleton and Drew Milne as a core text, this course explores key
            debates in Marxism and literary theory. Each session will supplement
            texts from the anthology with some texts by Marx and central Marxist
            theorists in order to examine key debates and dialogues, focussing
            on: Trotsky/ Lukacs/ Brecht; Adorno / Benjamin; Althusser / Macherey
            / Jameson; and Zizek / Laclau / Butler.</p>
          <p><a href= "Marx.htm">(Reading)</a>          </p>
          <p><strong>Lent Term</strong>
          </p>
          <p><a name="Jacobus" id="Jacobus"><strong>PROFESSOR M. JACOBUS, Psychoanalysis
                and Vision</strong></a></p>
          <p>Since Oedipus and the positing of castration anxiety, the founding
            myths of Freudian psychoanalysis have been concerned with sight and
            un-seeing, or blindness. More recently, the idea of a scopic drive
            has tended to focused on the gaze (Lacan) or on the relation between
            perception, hallucination, and negative hallucination (Winnicott,
            Bion, Andr&eacute; Green). This course will read psychoanalytic writing
            alongside philosophers such as Merleau-Ponty (The Visible Invisible),
            Derrida (The Truth in Painting, Memoirs of the Blind), critics such
            as Barthes (Image/Text, Camera Lucida), and recent art criticism
            that has drawn on psychoanalytic and theoretical texts, including
            Fried, Berger, T.J. Clark, and Krauss. Although not a visual culture
            course as such, it will make connections with past and present artists
            and art-works as well as with literary criticism by Scarry, Fisher,
            and others. </p>
          <p><a href= "PsychVisreading.htm">(Reading)</a>
          </p>
          <p><strong><a name="Trotter" id="Trotter">PROFESSOR D.TROTTER, 'Naturalism'
                 in Literature and Cinema</a>
          </strong> </p>
          <p> Naturalism was perhaps the late-c19th&#8217;s most significant
            contribution to the repertoire of plots and descriptive techniques
            available for figuring (and figuring out) human experience. Although
            it took various forms, in fiction and drama, its primary aim was
            to explore and exploit (physical, moral, and social) &#8216;lowness&#8217;.
            Naturalism let loose in the world a narrative which, rather than
            bind events into significance, as most narratives do, unbound them
            from it. The narrative unbinding was consistently a narrative of
          unbinding: of social and moral disintegration. </p>
          <p>These classes will not seek to define a Naturalist &#8216;tradition&#8217; in
            modern literature and cinema. Instead, they will ask why an impulse
            to Naturalism should so persistently have reasserted itself, in a
            wide variety of modes and contexts, throughout the c20th: in defiance
            of Modernism, in defiance of metafiction, in defiance of the hegemony
            of generic formula. </p>
          <p>The classes are intended to encourage various kinds of work towards
            a theory and a history of the &#8216;modern&#8217;. At issue are,
            or could be: the politics of style, in literature and film; genre,
            in literature and film; the relation between word and image; the
            gendering of stories of decline and disintegration; cultural &#8216;nation-building&#8217;;
            interpretation and/as aesthetic pleasure; interpretation and/as social
            pathology. There would be no objection to a focus on an individual
            writer or film-maker.</p>
          <p><a href= "NaturalismreadingMT05.htm">(Reading/viewing)</a> </p>
          <p><a name="Gopal" id="Gopal"><strong>DR P. GOPAL, The Post-Colonial Critic: Intellectuals, Power and Practice</strong></a> </p>
          <p>The figure of the critic/writer/intellectual will provide us a heuristic device with which to consider a range of concerns relevant to &#8216;postcolonial studies&#8217;: representation (in more than one sense, including &#8216;vertreten&#8217; and &#8216;darstellung&#8217;); theory in relation to revolutionary or transformative practice; violence; complicity; exile; subalternity; humanism; nationalism; marginality and &#8216;epistemic privilege&#8217;; and &#8216;speaking truth to power&#8217;. Writers to be discussed include Antonio Gramsci, Frantz Fanon, Edward Said, Gayatri Spivak, Benita Parry, Amitav Ghosh and Ranajit Guha. </p>
          <p><a href= "Postcolreading.htm">(Reading)</a> </p>
          <p>&nbsp; </p>
        </ul>
		<p></p>
      </li>
      <li>Option B courses may be selected from other M.Phils. in the English 
        Faculty where available, as well as from M.Phils. in other faculties (currently, 
        MML, History of Art and Architecture, HPS). These courses will be chosen 
        in consultation with your advisor and you will have to satisfy the host 
        M.Phil. that you are suitably qualified (e.g proficient in a foreign language). 
        Where your specific research interests justify it, you may be allowed 
        to take up to three of your four courses from other M.Phils. with the 
        special approval of the steering group.<br />
        <br />
      </li>
      <li>Alongside your course-work, you will participate in a group providing 
        a forum for intellectual exchange and professional training. In the first 
        term, this will take the form 
        <table border="0" align="right">
          <tr> 
            <td><img src="images/Crocodile.jpg" width="216" height="325" align="right" vspace="5" hspace="3" /></td>
          </tr>
          <tr> 
            <td align="center"> <font size="-1">Photo courtesy of Kettle's Yard</font></td>
          </tr>
        </table>
        of a faculty-facilitated reading group exploring relevant critical and 
        theoretical issues. In the second term, you will have the chance to present 
        your dissertation proposal in a pre-dissertation workshop. In the third 
        term, you will take part in a peer-led dissertation-writing group. <br />
        <br />
      </li>
      <li>Course requirements include a 4,000 word paper for one course at the 
        end of each term, along with a shorter (2,500 word) paper for the second 
        course, and a 12-15,000 word dissertation in the third term. Any courses 
        you take in other faculties will be assessed by the requirements for that 
        course in the host faculty. To prepare for your dissertation, you will 
        produce a detailed bibliography by the end of the first term, and a detailed 
        dissertation prospectus by the end of the second term, to be approved 
        by your advisor.<br />
        <br />
      </li>
      <li>In addition to familiarizing yourself with the resources of the University 
        Library and electronic resources for research, you will have the opportunity 
        to participate in the broader intellectual life of the Cambridge research 
        community. As well as graduate research seminars and reading groups in 
        the English Faculty, you may attend University lectures in English and 
        other Humanities faculties. Interdisciplinary seminars and reading groups 
        take place at the <a href="http://www.crassh.cam.ac.uk/">Centre for Research 
        in the Arts, Social Sciences, and Humanities (CRASSH)</a>. You are also 
        encouraged to make use of the University's language-learning facilities.</li>
    </ul>
    <h2><a name="faculty" id="faculty">Faculty Members: Criticism and Culture</a></h2>
    <p>The interests of those teaching the Criticism and Culture M.Phil. span, 
      for instance, philosophy and literature, visual culture, post-colonial and 
      commonwealth literature, psychoanalysis and literature, critical theory, 
      Marxist literary theory, and performance theory. Many faculty members also 
      have period-specific interests that range from Medieval and Renaissance 
      literature to twentieth-century and contemporary writing. Among those committed 
      to teaching for the M.Phil. are the following current members of the English 
      Faculty: Christopher Cannon, Peter de Bolla, Juliet Fleming, Priya Gopal, 
      John Harvey, David Hillman, Mary Jacobus, Simon Jarvis, and Drew Milne. 
      From time to time other faculty members may also offer courses and be available 
      to supervise individual research projects. You may want to consult the <a href="../faculty/index.htm">full 
      list of Members of the English Faculty</a> for the interests of faculty 
      and to contact potential supervisors in relation to your research interests. 
    </p>
