    <h2><a name="applications" id="applications">Entry Requirements and Application 
      Procedures</a></h2>
    <p>You may find it helpful to find out about <a 
      href="Funding.htm">funding for home 
      students</a> or <a 
      href="OSFunding.htm">funding for 
      overseas students</a> before you apply. You should also consult our guide 
      for <a 
      href="Grad_Info.htm">prospective 
      graduates</a>. All graduate students in <em><img src="images/bombay-1873.jpg" width="230" height="305" align="left" hspace="3" vspace="5" /></em>Cambridge 
      are members of a College as well as of a Faculty of the University, and 
      those applying through the Board of Graduate Studies for a place on the 
      course will find themselves invited to list a number of Colleges in order 
      of preference. It is a good idea to consult the <a 
      href="http://www.cam.ac.uk/CambUniv/Finding/Addresses/college.html">prospectuses 
      of a number of Colleges</a> before you apply. </p>
    <p>Applications are first considered by the Faculty. Potential supervisors 
      are then consulted. Successful applications are then offered to the Colleges 
      of the student's choice, and may be then passed on to the second or third 
      choice. Since this can be a lengthy process it is very much in the interests 
      of applicants to apply in good time (and before the <strong>new deadline 
      for applications of January 15th). Applicants are urged to make sure that 
      duplicates of their application materials are sent direct to the English 
      Faculty as well as to the Board of Graduate Studies (see general instructions 
      for admission to English).</strong></p>
    <table border="0" align="right">
      <tr> 
        <td><img src="images/sphinx.jpg" width="234" height="336" align="right" vspace="5" hspace="3" /></td>
      </tr>
      <tr> 
        <td align="center"><font size="-1">Photo courtesy of the Freud Museum</font></td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    <p>Applicants for funding should be aware that many funding bodies (e.g. the 
      <a href="http://www.ahrb.ac.uk">Arts and Humanities Research Council</a>) 
      require a firm acceptance from the University before they will consider 
      your application. If you hope to have a decision from the University in 
      time to apply for funding, you should apply well before the <strong>January 
      15th </strong>deadline. You may find it helpful in drawing up your funding 
      application to have had some discussion with the person assigned to be your 
      supervisor. Please consult the separate instructions for <a href= "http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/univ/gsprospectus/funding/overseas/applying/deadlines.html"> 
      application deadlines</a> on the Board of Graduate Studies website.</p>
    <p>Applicants should normally have a first-class honours degree or high II.i 
      , or its overseas/international equivalent (e.g. minimum 3.7 GPA). Applicants 
      whose first degrees are in other disciplines are always considered, provided 
      they can give an account of how their interest in literary study has developed. 
      We welcome qualified UK, EU, and overseas applicants (those for whom English 
      is not a first language will be required by the Board of Graduate Studies 
      to provide evidence of linguistic proficiency). </p>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
   
    <p>Applicants should include specific proposals for advanced study or research
      (of around 500 words). A piece of written work, of 5,000 - 7,500 words,
      should accompany a formal application. Applicants may submit any work they
      like, but it is worth choosing work which is recent and which relates to
      your proposed area of study, if this is available. Many applicants submit
      their undergraduate dissertation or similar extended piece of work. In
      reaching decisions about applications the Degree Committee takes particular
      account of: </p>
    <ul>
      <li><span class="mainbody">The applicant's academic record and references </span> </li>
      <li><span class="mainbody">Their suitability for the proposed course (including
          knowledge of foreign languages) </span> </li>
      <li><span class="mainbody">The applicant's research proposal, which should
          suggest a realistic program of work for a 15,000 word dissertation. </span> </li>
      <li><span class="mainbody">Whether a suitable supervisor can be found for
          the proposed research </span> </li>
      <li><span class="mainbody">The written work which a candidate submits in
          support of their application </span></li>
    </ul>
